Other trade-related acts were passed in the same session, including the Exportation Act 1660 ([12 Cha. 2](/12_Cha._2). c. 32), which banned the export of wool and wool-processing materials,&#91;34&#93; and the Tobacco Planting and Sowing Act 1660 ([12 Cha. 2](/12_Cha._2). c. 34), which prohibited growing tobacco in England and Ireland.&#91;35&#93; The former was intended to protect domestic woolen manufacturing by ensuring a cheap supply of raw materials; the latter was passed to eliminate competition for the colonies' main cash crop and protect the regulated royal revenue stream it generated. As the kingdoms of [England](/Kingdom_of_England) and [Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland) were still separate entities, the English act prompted the [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) to pass a similar navigation act.&#91;36&#93; After the [Act of Union 1707](/Act_of_Union_1707), Scottish ships, merchants, and mariners were granted the same privileges.

